00:13:52.539 --> 00:13:53.928
That's not the main thesis.
 

00:13:53.928 --> 00:13:57.751
The main thesis is to tell you
that what people had figured out

00:13:57.751 --> 00:14:00.527
by the seventeenth century is
that it travels,

00:14:00.527 --> 00:14:02.870
and it travels at a certain
speed.

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:07.657
Now you guys have learned
geometrical optics in high

00:14:07.657 --> 00:14:09.159
school, right?
 

00:14:09.159 --> 00:14:09.870
Everybody?
 

00:14:09.870 --> 00:14:15.909
Who has not seen geometrical
optics, lenses and mirrors?

00:14:15.909 --> 00:14:17.350
You've not seen?
 

00:14:17.350 --> 00:14:20.519
Okay, that's all right.
 

00:14:20.519 --> 00:14:23.832
But I will tell you,
I'll remind you what the other

00:14:23.832 --> 00:14:24.960
guys have seen.
 

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:27.960
I'm going to show you another
way to think about it.

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:34.407
First thing they teach you is
if light hits a mirror,

00:14:34.407 --> 00:14:41.597
it bounces off in such a way
that the angle of incidence is

00:14:41.597 --> 00:14:45.070
the angle of reflection.
 

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:48.687
Second thing they will teach
you is that if light travels

00:14:48.687 --> 00:14:51.080
from one medium to another
medium,

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:56.830
say this is air and say this is
glass,

00:14:56.830 --> 00:15:00.440
then the first thing to note is
that the velocity of light,

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:04.028
c, is the velocity in
vacuum.

00:15:04.028 --> 00:15:08.028
When light travels through a
medium, that's not the velocity.

00:15:08.028 --> 00:15:12.147
The velocity is altered by a
factor called n,

00:15:12.147 --> 00:15:17.232
which is bigger than 1 or equal
to 1, and n is called the

00:15:17.232 --> 00:15:20.139
refractive index of that medium.
 

00:15:20.139 --> 00:15:22.340
I think glass is like 1.33.
 

00:15:22.340 --> 00:15:26.380
Every medium has a refractive
index and the effective velocity

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:29.428
of light is slowed by this
factor, n.

00:15:29.428 --> 00:15:31.475
So let us say,
this medium,

00:15:31.475 --> 00:15:34.856
let's not call it air,
n_1,

00:15:34.856 --> 00:15:38.788
this is refractive index
n_2.

00:15:38.788 --> 00:15:43.494
If a beam of light comes like
this and hits this interface,

00:15:43.494 --> 00:15:45.360
it won't go straight.
 

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:49.509
It will generally deviate from
its original direction,

00:15:49.509 --> 00:15:53.509
and if you call this the theta
incident,

00:15:53.509 --> 00:15:57.330
and you call this the theta
refracted,

00:15:57.330 --> 00:16:00.240
then there is a law,
called Snell's law,

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:02.450
which says n_1
sinθ

00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:04.711
_1 is
n_2 times

00:16:04.711 --> 00:16:06.418
sinθ_2.
 

00:16:06.418 --> 00:16:08.750
And theta is measured--in fact,
let me call it

00:16:08.750 --> 00:16:11.860
θ_1 and
θ_2.

00:16:11.860 --> 00:16:17.960
This is called Snell's law.
 

00:16:17.960 --> 00:16:19.440
Look, the way to think of the
law is,

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:21.977
if n_2 is
bigger, then sinθ

00:16:21.977 --> 00:16:24.408
will be smaller,
so this angle would be smaller.

00:16:24.408 --> 00:16:28.009
So when light goes from a rare
medium to a dense medium,

00:16:28.009 --> 00:16:30.825
it will go even closer to the
perpendicular,

00:16:30.825 --> 00:16:32.200
or to the normal.
 

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:35.456
And if you run the ray
backwards, from the dense medium

00:16:35.456 --> 00:16:38.893
to the rare medium at some
angle, it will go away from the

00:16:38.893 --> 00:16:40.158
normal even more.
 

00:16:40.158 --> 00:16:43.620
That was done and that was
measured and all that stuff.

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:46.980
Then you can look at more
things.

00:16:46.980 --> 00:16:53.779
You look at mirrors,
parabolic mirrors,

00:16:53.779 --> 00:16:56.899
where you know if a light ray
comes like that,

00:16:56.899 --> 00:17:00.389
parallel to the axis,
it goes through what's called a

00:17:00.389 --> 00:17:01.330
focal point.
 

00:17:01.330 --> 00:17:04.296
Every parallel ray goes through
the focal point,

00:17:04.296 --> 00:17:07.009
so you can use it to focus the
light ray.

00:17:07.009 --> 00:17:07.740
That's what you see.
 

00:17:07.740 --> 00:17:11.308
Whenever you have these
antennas, your own satellite

00:17:11.308 --> 00:17:15.440
dish, here's the dish in which
the rays come and they're all

00:17:15.440 --> 00:17:17.328
focused onto one point.
 

00:17:17.328 --> 00:17:20.857
That's where you put your probe
that picks up the signal from

00:17:20.857 --> 00:17:21.798
the satellite.
 

00:17:21.798 --> 00:17:26.002
It's a way to focus all the
light into one place,

00:17:26.002 --> 00:17:30.993
so it's a property of these
concave mirrors that they will

00:17:30.993 --> 00:17:34.759
focus all the light at the focal
point.

00:17:34.759 --> 00:17:36.690
Then you learn other stuff.
 

00:17:36.690 --> 00:17:40.444
If you don't have the object at
infinity sending parallel rays,

00:17:40.444 --> 00:17:43.048
if you have an object here,
what happens?

00:17:43.048 --> 00:17:45.798
Well, you have to do other
constructions.

00:17:45.798 --> 00:17:48.259
If you have an object here,
for example,

00:17:48.259 --> 00:17:51.098
you want to know what image
will be formed.

00:17:51.098 --> 00:17:54.487
You draw a parallel line and
that goes through the focal

00:17:54.487 --> 00:17:54.980
point.
 

00:17:54.980 --> 00:17:57.009
You draw a line through the
focal point.

00:17:57.009 --> 00:18:01.452
That comes out parallel,
and where they meet is your

00:18:01.452 --> 00:18:02.150
image.
 

00:18:02.150 --> 00:18:03.785
And this is called
h_1,

00:18:03.785 --> 00:18:05.380
this is called
h_2.

00:18:05.380 --> 00:18:08.546
That distance is called
u, that's called

00:18:08.546 --> 00:18:12.606
v, and you have this
result, 1/u 1/v is

00:18:12.606 --> 00:18:13.640
1/f.
 

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:17.517
By the way, there is no
universal agreement on what to

00:18:17.517 --> 00:18:19.200
call these distances.
 

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:21.582
Some people call it i
and o for image and

00:18:21.582 --> 00:18:21.980
object.
 

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:23.980
When I was growing up,
they called it u and

00:18:23.980 --> 00:18:24.430
v.
 

00:18:24.430 --> 00:18:31.339
I don't care what you want to
call it, but this is the law.

00:18:31.339 --> 00:18:35.588
Then you've got lenses.
 

00:18:35.588 --> 00:18:41.259
This is a piece of glass and it
has the property that when you

00:18:41.259 --> 00:18:46.464
shine parallel light from one
side, it all focuses on the

00:18:46.464 --> 00:18:47.859
other side.
 

00:18:47.859 --> 00:18:53.588
That's called the focal length.
 

00:18:53.588 --> 00:18:57.022
And if you have an object here,
it will go and form an image on

00:18:57.022 --> 00:19:00.115
the other side,
which will be upside down and

00:19:00.115 --> 00:19:02.720
that also obeys the same
equation,

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:06.305
except u is the distance
of the object and v is

00:19:06.305 --> 00:19:09.950
the distance of the image and
f is the focal length.

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:12.650
So there's a whole bunch of
things you learn.

00:19:12.650 --> 00:19:15.690
That's all I want you to know.
 

00:19:15.690 --> 00:19:20.165
Then there are some tricky
issues you must have seen

00:19:20.165 --> 00:19:24.017
yourself,
that if you got a lens that's

00:19:24.017 --> 00:19:29.750
not concave but convex,
like this, and if you shine

00:19:29.750 --> 00:19:33.470
light on that guy,
what will happen?

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:37.631
This parallel ray of light,
you can sort of imagine,

00:19:37.631 --> 00:19:39.588
will go off like that.
 

00:19:39.588 --> 00:19:43.762
In fact, the way it will go off
is as if it came from some point

00:19:43.762 --> 00:19:45.420
called the focal point.
 

00:19:45.420 --> 00:19:47.732
In other words,
these rays of light in this

00:19:47.732 --> 00:19:50.376
mirror, instead of really
focusing at some point,

00:19:50.376 --> 00:19:52.470
seem to come from the focal
point.

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:56.967
And if you draw a ray of light
here, since that is a vertical

00:19:56.967 --> 00:20:00.190
part of the mirror,
you use i = r.

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:02.068
That will go off at i =r.
 

00:20:02.068 --> 00:20:06.144
That ray of light when seen by
person here will seem to come

00:20:06.144 --> 00:20:10.150
from there, and if you join
them, you get an image here.

00:20:10.150 --> 00:20:13.608
That's the virtual image,
in the sense that this is a

00:20:13.608 --> 00:20:17.467
concave mirror--convex mirror
like the one you have in your

00:20:17.467 --> 00:20:18.000
car.
 

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.680
And if forms a reduced image of
the object.

00:20:21.680 --> 00:20:24.868
Okay, so this is the scene from
Jurassic Park.

00:20:24.868 --> 00:20:27.608
That's the dinosaur,
and there's the Jurassic--

00:20:27.608 --> 00:20:28.930
I mean, the image of that,
and it says,

00:20:28.930 --> 00:20:31.270
"Objects may be bigger
than what they appear in the

00:20:31.270 --> 00:20:31.910
mirror."
 

00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:34.942
That's what it's all about,
because one of these mirrors

00:20:34.942 --> 00:20:37.367
will make an image,
but it's called a virtual

00:20:37.367 --> 00:20:37.920
image.
 

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:39.323
In other words,
if you put a screen there,

00:20:39.323 --> 00:20:40.180
you won't see anything.
 

00:20:40.180 --> 00:20:42.019
It's on the other side of the
mirror.

00:20:42.019 --> 00:20:44.395
Here, if you put a screen,
if you put a candle here and

00:20:44.395 --> 00:20:46.509
put a screen here,
you will see a bright image of

00:20:46.509 --> 00:20:47.170
the candle.
 

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:49.828
So this is a real image,
and that's a virtual image.

00:20:49.828 --> 00:20:51.861
The way you do these
calculations,

00:20:51.861 --> 00:20:54.938
you use the same formula,
except f will be a

00:20:54.938 --> 00:20:56.170
negative number.
 

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:59.061
Instead of really focusing,
it anti-focuses,

00:20:59.061 --> 00:21:01.145
so the focal point,
if you want,

00:21:01.145 --> 00:21:03.769
is on the wrong side of the
mirror.

00:21:03.769 --> 00:21:07.147
You'll get all the right
answers if you use a negative

00:21:07.147 --> 00:21:07.848
f.
 

00:21:07.848 --> 00:21:11.332
So your textbook will have many
examples of how to solve these

00:21:11.332 --> 00:21:13.160
problems, very simple algebra.
 

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:16.339
But what I want to do,
since many of you have seen

00:21:16.339 --> 00:21:19.292
this,
and to make it interesting for

00:21:19.292 --> 00:21:22.991
you,
is to show you there is a

00:21:22.991 --> 00:21:28.163
single unifying principle,
just one principle,

00:21:28.163 --> 00:21:31.480
from which I can derive all
these laws.

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:34.791
All the things I mentioned,
this is why I didn't stop and

00:21:34.791 --> 00:21:37.454
go into detail,
every single one of them comes

00:21:37.454 --> 00:21:39.230
from one single principle.
 

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:44.450
Anybody know what that
principle might be?

00:21:44.450 --> 00:21:46.009
Have you heard of anything?
 

00:21:46.009 --> 00:21:47.048
Yes?
 

00:21:47.048 --> 00:21:47.809
Student:  I don't know
how to pronounce the name.

00:21:47.809 --> 00:21:49.058
It starts with an "H."
 

00:21:49.058 --> 00:21:50.470
Prof: You mean Huygens'
principle?

00:21:50.470 --> 00:21:51.210
Student:  Yes.
 

00:21:51.210 --> 00:21:53.470
Prof: No,
that's a different guy.

00:21:53.470 --> 00:21:58.029
This is the famous Fermat,
who had this theorem with prime

00:21:58.029 --> 00:21:58.828
numbers.
 

00:21:58.828 --> 00:22:03.817
His principle says light will
go from start to finish in a

00:22:03.817 --> 00:22:07.579
path that takes the least amount
of time.

00:22:07.579 --> 00:22:09.519
That's the path it will take.
 

00:22:09.519 --> 00:22:11.440
That's the Principle of Least
Time.

00:22:11.440 --> 00:22:27.038
 
 

00:22:27.038 --> 00:22:30.308
Now we find a lot of pleasure
when we can derive many,

00:22:30.308 --> 00:22:34.200
many things from a single
principle and you will see then,

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:37.448
all the stuff I wrote,
I can deduce from this one

00:22:37.448 --> 00:22:40.630
principle and that's what I want
to do today.

00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:42.069
So you don't have to carry all
that baggage.

00:22:42.069 --> 00:22:43.809
You can derive everything.
 

00:22:43.809 --> 00:22:45.920
So let's see how it goes.
 

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:49.260
So first let's say I am here
and you are here,

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:50.970
you send me a signal.
 

00:22:50.970 --> 00:22:52.769
What's the path it will take?
 

00:22:52.769 --> 00:22:54.750
Where is the path of least time?
 

00:22:54.750 --> 00:22:57.650
And everybody knows that's a
straight line.

00:22:57.650 --> 00:22:59.769
No point going any other way.
 

00:22:59.769 --> 00:23:03.526
So that tells you first,
light travels in straight lines

00:23:03.526 --> 00:23:05.778
when there's no other obstacle.
 

00:23:05.778 --> 00:23:11.196
The next possibility is,
I want the light--let me do

00:23:11.196 --> 00:23:17.568
this right because I'm going to
really draw some pictures.

00:23:17.568 --> 00:23:23.787
I want the light to hit the
mirror and then come to me,

00:23:23.787 --> 00:23:26.319
so it's like a race.
 

00:23:26.319 --> 00:23:27.640
You are here.
 

00:23:27.640 --> 00:23:31.609
You've got to touch the wall
and go to the finish line.

00:23:31.609 --> 00:23:33.309
Whoever gets there first wins.
 

00:23:33.309 --> 00:23:37.210
That's the path light will take.
 

00:23:37.210 --> 00:23:40.259
Now there are different
attitudes you can have.

00:23:40.259 --> 00:23:43.410
First is, you can start
wandering like this.

00:23:43.410 --> 00:23:46.861
You know that person's a loser,
because that's not the way to

00:23:46.861 --> 00:23:48.068
optimize your time.
 

00:23:48.068 --> 00:23:50.740
So we don't even listen to that
person.

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:52.858
There are other reasonable
people who may have a different

00:23:52.858 --> 00:23:53.118
view.
 

00:23:53.118 --> 00:23:55.699
One person may say,
"Look, he told me to touch

00:23:55.699 --> 00:23:58.640
the wall, so I'm going to get
that out of my way first.

00:23:58.640 --> 00:24:01.430
Then I'm going to go
there."

00:24:01.430 --> 00:24:03.250
Fine, that's a possibility.
 

00:24:03.250 --> 00:24:05.836
Another person can say,
"Well, let me touch the

00:24:05.836 --> 00:24:08.678
wall right in front of this
person, then run over to meet

00:24:08.678 --> 00:24:09.440
the person.
 

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:11.269
That's another
possibility."

00:24:11.269 --> 00:24:13.618
So there are different options
open to you.

00:24:13.618 --> 00:24:18.185
And we've got to find from all
these possible paths the one of

00:24:18.185 --> 00:24:19.160
least time.
 

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:20.798
That's the goal.
 

00:24:20.798 --> 00:24:23.492
Now I already said,
when you look at paths,

00:24:23.492 --> 00:24:27.019
the path to the mirror has got
to be a straight line.

00:24:27.019 --> 00:24:30.838
You gain nothing by wiggling
around.

00:24:30.838 --> 00:24:34.199
And the path back from the
mirror to the receiving point

00:24:34.199 --> 00:24:37.498
should also be a straight line,
because the winner lies

00:24:37.498 --> 00:24:38.720
somewhere there.
 

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:42.305
Anybody who doesn't follow a
straight line in free space is

00:24:42.305 --> 00:24:43.480
not going to win.
 

00:24:43.480 --> 00:24:47.030
So the only freedom you have,
the only thing you want to ask,

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:49.752
is the following:
"Where should I hit that

00:24:49.752 --> 00:24:50.759
mirror?"
 

00:24:50.759 --> 00:24:51.558
right?
 

00:24:51.558 --> 00:24:56.779
So let's call that point where
you hit as x.

00:24:56.779 --> 00:25:01.058
Let's say the distance between
these two points is L.

00:25:01.058 --> 00:25:04.258
This is at some height
h_1,

00:25:04.258 --> 00:25:07.680
this is at some height
h_2.

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:11.589
So what I will do,
is I will simply calculate the

00:25:11.589 --> 00:25:16.558
time, then find the x for
which the time is minimum.

00:25:16.558 --> 00:25:18.880
So what's the time taken for
the first segment?

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:21.440
So let's find the total time.
 

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:23.663
It will be the distance,
d_1,

00:25:23.663 --> 00:25:25.642
divided by the velocity of
light distance

00:25:25.642 --> 00:25:28.509
d_2 divided by
the velocity of light.

00:25:28.509 --> 00:25:31.240
d_1,
you can see,

00:25:31.240 --> 00:25:36.009
is h_1^(2)
x^(2),

00:25:36.009 --> 00:25:43.998
divided by c
h_2^(2) L -

00:25:43.998 --> 00:25:49.910
