00:39:05.550 --> 00:39:08.827
So if you were to design a
surface so that if you shot

00:39:08.827 --> 00:39:11.503
something one point,
it will all end up here,

00:39:11.503 --> 00:39:13.699
all the light from here will
focus here,

00:39:13.699 --> 00:39:17.239
you should build an ellipse,
and send the light from one

00:39:17.239 --> 00:39:18.139
focal point.
 

00:39:18.139 --> 00:39:21.396
Likewise, if you talk,
also the sound will come to

00:39:21.396 --> 00:39:22.659
that other point.
 

00:39:22.659 --> 00:39:25.632
Now sound waves behave more
like waves rather than

00:39:25.632 --> 00:39:27.817
geometrical optics,
but if it's high,

00:39:27.817 --> 00:39:29.820
long, short wavelength sound.
 

00:39:29.820 --> 00:39:33.320
Suppose you're talking to your
dog, then you can talk to the

00:39:33.320 --> 00:39:34.268
dog from here.
 

00:39:34.268 --> 00:39:38.179
At sufficiently high frequency,
the dog will hear it here.

00:39:38.179 --> 00:39:39.280
So it's a focusing effect.
 

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:43.947
So the way focusing works,
is that there's more than one

00:39:43.947 --> 00:39:46.750
way to go from start to finish.
 

00:39:46.750 --> 00:39:48.789
But you are supposed to follow
the Principle of Least Time.

00:39:48.789 --> 00:39:52.230
That means all those paths take
the same time.

00:39:52.230 --> 00:39:53.639
That's the key.
 

00:39:53.639 --> 00:39:57.873
When you look at a mirror in
front of--an object in front of

00:39:57.873 --> 00:40:02.539
a mirror, there's only one path,
hit the mirror and bounce out.

00:40:02.539 --> 00:40:07.144
But if you have a geometry like
this one, curved,

00:40:07.144 --> 00:40:09.159
then it's not true.
 

00:40:09.159 --> 00:40:15.110
There is more than one way to
go from start to finish.

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:25.139
Okay, so now let us ask how you
build a focusing mirror.

00:40:25.139 --> 00:40:26.659
Here's what we want to do.
 

00:40:26.659 --> 00:40:28.480
So this is not very practical.
 

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:32.170
This is very useful,
but it's not what I'm talking

00:40:32.170 --> 00:40:36.614
about, because I didn't discuss
that in things you knew from

00:40:36.614 --> 00:40:37.820
high school.
 

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:43.949
Here's what you knew from high
school, how to make a focusing

00:40:43.949 --> 00:40:44.869
mirror.
 

00:40:44.869 --> 00:40:48.605
So the deal is,
light's going to come from some

00:40:48.605 --> 00:40:52.503
object at infinity,
therefore it's coming in some

00:40:52.503 --> 00:40:56.239
parallel lines from a very
distant object.

00:40:56.239 --> 00:41:01.813
You want to put some mirror of
some shape so that every one of

00:41:01.813 --> 00:41:06.110
these guys will come to the same
focal point.

00:41:06.110 --> 00:41:07.630
You can ask,
"Can I even design such a

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:07.920
thing?
 

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:09.780
Is it possible?
 

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:11.340
If so, what do I have to do?
 

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:13.820
What's the shape of the
object?"

00:41:13.820 --> 00:41:15.050
So let's do the following.
 

00:41:15.050 --> 00:41:20.710
Let's take the ray that goes
along the axis of this thing.

00:41:20.710 --> 00:41:23.579
It goes here.
 

00:41:23.579 --> 00:41:27.577
It goes to that mirror,
hits the mirror,

00:41:27.577 --> 00:41:31.780
then it comes back a distance
f.

00:41:31.780 --> 00:41:35.150
So in the time it takes to go
from here to here,

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:39.023
had it continued going,
it would have gone to this wall

00:41:39.023 --> 00:41:41.750
here, also at a distance
f.

00:41:41.750 --> 00:41:43.480
Do you agree?
 

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:47.010
The time it takes for it to hit
the mirror and come to the focal

00:41:47.010 --> 00:41:49.980
point is the same as the time it
would have taken,

00:41:49.980 --> 00:41:54.786
but for the mirror,
to go the other side the same

00:41:54.786 --> 00:41:56.789
distance f.
 

00:41:56.789 --> 00:42:01.097
Okay, now I take a second ray
that's not on the symmetry axis,

00:42:01.097 --> 00:42:02.579
but above the axis.
 

00:42:02.579 --> 00:42:06.382
It comes here,
and having come here,

00:42:06.382 --> 00:42:11.708
if it has to take the same time
as the other beam,

00:42:11.708 --> 00:42:14.969
it's the time to go there.
 

00:42:14.969 --> 00:42:19.369
But you want it to instead come
here.

00:42:19.369 --> 00:42:22.250
So how will that happen?
 

00:42:22.250 --> 00:42:26.719
What will ensure that that
happens?

00:42:26.719 --> 00:42:31.750
Can you guys think of what
condition you have?

00:42:31.750 --> 00:42:33.449
Yes?
 

00:42:33.449 --> 00:42:36.079
Student:  The two
distances need to be the same.

00:42:36.079 --> 00:42:39.309
The distance from the mirror to
the--

00:42:39.309 --> 00:42:40.219
Prof: Do you understand
that?

00:42:40.219 --> 00:42:41.530
That's very important.
 

00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:46.599
That distance and that distance
have to be equal.

00:42:46.599 --> 00:42:49.130
Let's be very clear on why we
are doing that.

00:42:49.130 --> 00:42:50.719
See, these guys came from
infinity.

00:42:50.719 --> 00:42:52.590
They've been traveling in a
parallel line.

00:42:52.590 --> 00:42:56.103
Start with some plane here,
so that everybody is counted

00:42:56.103 --> 00:42:58.980
from now on and see how much
time you take.

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:02.793
The ray from this center goes
to the mirror and goes an extra

00:43:02.793 --> 00:43:05.909
distance f,
because that's what it does.

00:43:05.909 --> 00:43:08.824
So that's the distance to which
any distance these rays would

00:43:08.824 --> 00:43:10.380
have gone, but for the mirror.
 

00:43:10.380 --> 00:43:13.349
That's how much time you have.
 

00:43:13.349 --> 00:43:16.333
So if you went there and you
want to turn around and come

00:43:16.333 --> 00:43:18.228
here,
that extra distance better be

00:43:18.228 --> 00:43:20.460
equal to the distance to go to
that plane,

00:43:20.460 --> 00:43:26.699
because that's the same time
for everything.

00:43:26.699 --> 00:43:30.420
So that's the condition of the
surface.

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:35.096
It is a surface with a property
that its distance,

00:43:35.096 --> 00:43:40.057
any point on that curve,
has the same distance from a

00:43:40.057 --> 00:43:43.590
fixed point as from a fixed
line.

00:43:43.590 --> 00:43:47.739
If you can find that,
that's the surface you want.

00:43:47.739 --> 00:43:50.409
Now that happens to be a
parabola, but we'll derive that,

00:43:50.409 --> 00:43:52.460
but that's what you learn in
high school.

00:43:52.460 --> 00:43:57.840
A parabola is a curve which is
equidistant from a point and

00:43:57.840 --> 00:43:59.139
from a line.
 

00:43:59.139 --> 00:44:00.989
Distance to the point is very
clear.

00:44:00.989 --> 00:44:03.681
Distance to the line is
obtained by drawing a

00:44:03.681 --> 00:44:07.780
perpendicular and measuring that
distance, the shortest distance.

00:44:07.780 --> 00:44:09.880
So I'm just going to equate
these two, that's it.

00:44:09.880 --> 00:44:11.940
That will give me the equation
for this curve.

00:44:11.940 --> 00:44:14.925
So let this graph,
the shape of the mirror I'm

00:44:14.925 --> 00:44:17.780
trying to design,
let this be the origin.

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:20.594
This is some point with
coordinate x and

00:44:20.594 --> 00:44:24.204
y, and y is some
function of x that I'm

00:44:24.204 --> 00:44:25.550
going to find out.
 

00:44:25.550 --> 00:44:26.119
That's the goal.
 

00:44:26.119 --> 00:44:29.489
What's the function y of
x that you want?

00:44:29.489 --> 00:44:35.550
So let's find out the different
distances.

00:44:35.550 --> 00:44:40.329
So what is that distance it has
to travel?

00:44:40.329 --> 00:44:43.768
You can see,
x is the coordinate of

00:44:43.768 --> 00:44:44.860
this point.
 

00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:48.945
It's got to do that and another
extra f on the other

00:44:48.945 --> 00:44:49.440
side.
 

00:44:49.440 --> 00:44:52.699
So going horizontally,
it's got to do an x here

00:44:52.699 --> 00:44:56.018
and an f there,
so it's got to do x f.

00:44:56.018 --> 00:45:01.510
That's the distance from the
mirror to this fictitious plane.

00:45:01.510 --> 00:45:03.239
That's the time they have.
 

00:45:03.239 --> 00:45:09.210
They all have the time to go to
this fictitious plane.

00:45:09.210 --> 00:45:12.820
So I'm going to equate that to
this distance.

00:45:12.820 --> 00:45:15.639
This one, you've got to use
Pythagoras' Theorem.

00:45:15.639 --> 00:45:20.139
So this height is y.
 

00:45:20.139 --> 00:45:26.030
So it's y^(2) (f −
x)^(2),

00:45:26.030 --> 00:45:29.969
because this side here is f
- x,

00:45:29.969 --> 00:45:32.639
because the whole distance is
f and that's x.

00:45:32.639 --> 00:45:33.199
You follow that?
 

00:45:33.199 --> 00:45:35.389
(x,y) is the coordinate
of this point.

00:45:35.389 --> 00:45:36.590
You drop a line down here.
 

00:45:36.590 --> 00:45:37.889
That distance is x.
 

00:45:37.889 --> 00:45:39.750
This is f - x and that's
y.

00:45:39.750 --> 00:45:40.679
That's that length.
 

00:45:40.679 --> 00:45:44.530
You want these two to be equal.
 

00:45:44.530 --> 00:45:46.519
So if you have a square root,
you know what you have to do.

00:45:46.519 --> 00:45:48.039
You've got to square both sides.
 

00:45:48.039 --> 00:45:55.936
You square both sides,
you get x^(2) f^(2) 

00:45:55.936 --> 00:46:03.349
2xf = y^(2) (f −
x)^(2).

00:46:03.349 --> 00:46:11.717
So x^(2) cancels,
f^(2) cancels,

00:46:11.717 --> 00:46:18.969
then I get y^(2) =
4xf.

00:46:18.969 --> 00:46:21.880
That's the equation of the
parabola.

00:46:21.880 --> 00:46:26.751
You're probably used to drawing
parabolas that look like this,

00:46:26.751 --> 00:46:28.829
but it's the same thing.
 

00:46:28.829 --> 00:46:30.550
I've just turned it around.
 

00:46:30.550 --> 00:46:35.648
So if you go a distance y
here, then this x is

00:46:35.648 --> 00:46:38.070
quadratic in the y.
 

00:46:38.070 --> 00:46:41.155
So that's the equation,
that's the process by which you

00:46:41.155 --> 00:46:44.469
can design a mirror that will
focus light from infinity.

00:46:44.469 --> 00:46:47.420
So it can be done.
 

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:49.710
Likewise, if you said in the
elliptical case,

00:46:49.710 --> 00:46:52.708
"Can I find a surface
inside which the distance will

00:46:52.708 --> 00:46:55.331
go from here to there after
touching the figure is

00:46:55.331 --> 00:46:57.579
independent of where I touch
it?"

00:46:57.579 --> 00:46:59.610
the equation you will get will
be an ellipse.

00:46:59.610 --> 00:47:01.219
That's more complicated to
derive.

00:47:01.219 --> 00:47:02.530
This is a lot easier to derive.
 

00:47:02.530 --> 00:47:04.639
This is the equation of the
parabola.

00:47:04.639 --> 00:47:09.010
So if you want to build a dish
that will really focus light,

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:11.898
no matter how far,
how wide the beam is,

00:47:11.898 --> 00:47:13.380
this will do it.
 

00:47:13.380 --> 00:47:16.030
Parabolic mirrors is something
like what Hubble would use.

00:47:16.030 --> 00:47:18.869
Anybody would use parabolic
mirrors,

00:47:18.869 --> 00:47:23.887
but there is a cheap trick
people use if they cannot afford

00:47:23.887 --> 00:47:26.788
a parabola,
because it's very hard to

00:47:26.788 --> 00:47:29.219
design things in a parabolic
shape.

00:47:29.219 --> 00:47:32.320
Do you know what the simplest
solution is?

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:33.849
It's a sphere.
 

00:47:33.849 --> 00:47:37.039
Now a sphere is not quite a
parabola,

00:47:37.039 --> 00:47:40.739
but you can imagine that if you
have a parabola like this,

00:47:40.739 --> 00:47:43.885
and have a sphere,
the sphere can sort of mimic

00:47:43.885 --> 00:47:46.280
the parabola up to some
distance.

00:47:46.280 --> 00:47:48.579
Then of course it will deviate.
 

00:47:48.579 --> 00:47:52.083
But if you promise that you'll
only take beams very near the

00:47:52.083 --> 00:47:54.766
axis,
then the two are just as good,

00:47:54.766 --> 00:47:59.108
except it's easier to make a
spherical mirror than to make a

00:47:59.108 --> 00:48:00.579
parabolic mirror.
 

00:48:00.579 --> 00:48:03.360
But if you've got the money,
parabola is what you want.

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:06.550
Otherwise, this is the cheaper
solution.

00:48:06.550 --> 00:48:09.721
So let's ask ourselves the
following question:

00:48:09.721 --> 00:48:13.880
if I take a sphere of radius R
and I slice a part of it,

00:48:13.880 --> 00:48:16.902
okay, it's a hollow sphere and
I slice a part of it and I paint

00:48:16.902 --> 00:48:19.050
it with silver,
so I've got a mirror,

00:48:19.050 --> 00:48:21.505
this part of it,
what will be the focal length

00:48:21.505 --> 00:48:21.929
of that?
 

00:48:21.929 --> 00:48:25.679
That's what we are asking.
 

00:48:25.679 --> 00:48:31.653
I get that by saying the
following: so here is that

00:48:31.653 --> 00:48:32.730
sphere.
 

00:48:32.730 --> 00:48:35.431
It's got radius R,
and there is some point

00:48:35.431 --> 00:48:37.409
(x,y) on that sphere.
 

00:48:37.409 --> 00:48:43.530
Then if this is my origin,
the equation for a sphere will

00:48:43.530 --> 00:48:48.121
be (x −
R)^(2)  y^(2) =

00:48:48.121 --> 00:48:49.980
R^(2).
 

00:48:49.980 --> 00:48:52.668
See, normally is x^(2)
y^(2) = R^(2),

00:48:52.668 --> 00:48:53.099
right?
 

00:48:53.099 --> 00:48:55.829
That's when the origin is at
the center of the sphere.

00:48:55.829 --> 00:48:59.777
But the center of this sphere
is at a point x = R,

00:48:59.777 --> 00:49:03.655
so the equation in this
coordinate system will look like

00:49:03.655 --> 00:49:04.289
this.
 

00:49:04.289 --> 00:49:12.137
So you open everything out,
you get x^(2) R^(2) - 2xr

00:49:12.137 --> 00:49:18.844
 y^(2) =
R^(2). You cancel the

00:49:18.844 --> 00:49:26.550
R^(2) and you get
y^(2) = 2xr x^(2).

00:49:26.550 --> 00:49:31.621
I want you to compare this
equation to the equation for a

00:49:31.621 --> 00:49:33.070
real parabola.
 

00:49:33.070 --> 00:49:34.679
They don't look the same.
 

00:49:34.679 --> 00:49:45.869
Yes?
 

00:49:45.869 --> 00:49:50.820
Student:
Yes, that's correct.

00:49:50.820 --> 00:49:53.090
Yes.
 

00:49:53.090 --> 00:49:56.440
Now the way to think about this
is that but for this

00:49:56.440 --> 00:50:00.367
−x^(2) term,
this equation looks like a

00:50:00.367 --> 00:50:03.360
parabola,
but if you compare the two,

00:50:03.360 --> 00:50:06.409
you find that 4xf =
2xR.

00:50:06.409 --> 00:50:09.940
That means R = 2f.
 

00:50:09.940 --> 00:50:13.530
Or, if you like,
the focal length is R/2.

00:50:13.530 --> 00:50:15.577
But we're not done yet,
because I just threw away the

00:50:15.577 --> 00:50:16.130
second term.
 

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:19.610
I've got to give you a reason
for throwing the second term.

00:50:19.610 --> 00:50:22.577
So here is where you've got to
get used to the following notion

00:50:22.577 --> 00:50:23.869
of big and small numbers.
 

00:50:23.869 --> 00:50:28.788
Whenever you deal with a mirror
or a lens, things like u,

00:50:28.788 --> 00:50:33.289
v, f are all going to be
treated as big numbers.

00:50:33.289 --> 00:50:38.088
Things like y that take
you off the axis are going to be

00:50:38.088 --> 00:50:40.179
considered small numbers.
 

00:50:40.179 --> 00:50:43.809
Things like x are even
smaller.

00:50:43.809 --> 00:50:49.072
So the hierarchy is,
u, v,

00:50:49.072 --> 00:50:54.335
f, big,
y is small,

00:50:54.335 --> 00:50:59.269
x is small squared.
 

00:50:59.269 --> 00:51:00.880
You can see that already.
 

00:51:00.880 --> 00:51:04.239
Suppose someone tells you to
look at this equation.

00:51:04.239 --> 00:51:05.329
You can look at the two terms.
 

00:51:05.329 --> 00:51:08.336
One is x times R,
other is x times

00:51:08.336 --> 00:51:08.949
x.
 

00:51:08.949 --> 00:51:11.213
So x times R
beats x times x,

00:51:11.213 --> 00:51:13.760
because one is a small number,
one is a small number squared.

00:51:13.760 --> 00:51:15.900
So we're going to drop that
term.

00:51:15.900 --> 00:51:18.585
Then we get,
in that approximation,

00:51:18.585 --> 00:51:19.929
this condition.
 

00:51:19.929 --> 00:51:22.139
But that had to be such an
approximation,

00:51:22.139 --> 00:51:24.679
because a sphere can never
equal a parabola.

00:51:24.679 --> 00:51:28.132
It can look like a parabola
only for small deviations from

00:51:28.132 --> 00:51:28.800
the axis.
 

00:51:28.800 --> 00:51:32.449
This is cautioning you that if
your rays come too far off,

00:51:32.449 --> 00:51:35.070
like way over there,
then the x times

00:51:35.070 --> 00:51:38.911
R term will be comparable
to the x^(2) term and it

00:51:38.911 --> 00:51:41.349
will no longer look like a
parabola.

00:51:41.349 --> 00:51:42.469
So you should be very clear.
 

00:51:42.469 --> 00:51:46.029
When you make a real parabolic
mirror, it will focus rays,

00:51:46.029 --> 00:51:48.840
no matter how far they are from
the origin.

00:51:48.840 --> 00:51:51.869
If I take a spherical
approximation to it,

00:51:51.869 --> 00:51:56.380
it will work only if the rays
are very close to the center.

00:51:56.380 --> 00:51:59.050
So here's a spherical mirror.
 

00:51:59.050 --> 00:52:02.585
You cannot have the rays going
too far from here,

00:52:02.585 --> 00:52:06.119
in the scale of u,
v and f. Yes?

00:52:06.119 --> 00:52:09.907
Student:  With the first
equation, if f = 0,

00:52:09.907 --> 00:52:11.170
isn't it a plane?
 

00:52:11.170 --> 00:52:12.030
Prof: Yes.
 

00:52:12.030 --> 00:52:15.887
Student:  But the focal
point isn't at the origin,

00:52:15.887 --> 00:52:16.440
is it?
 

00:52:16.440 --> 00:52:19.990
Because the plane here has--
Prof: Yeah,

00:52:19.990 --> 00:52:21.219
what did you want to do for
that one?

00:52:21.219 --> 00:52:25.336
Student:  If you put
f = 0,

00:52:25.336 --> 00:52:28.940
so you have the focal length =
0.

00:52:28.940 --> 00:52:31.059
Prof: Plane mirror is
focal length = infinity.

00:52:31.059 --> 00:52:32.434
Student:  Infinity.
 

00:52:32.434 --> 00:52:34.018
Oh, it's the other way around.
 

00:52:34.018 --> 00:52:34.389
Okay.
 

00:52:34.389 --> 00:52:36.286
Prof: It's the fact
there is bending that's focusing

00:52:36.286 --> 00:52:36.449
it.
 

00:52:36.449 --> 00:52:39.659
As you straighten it out more
and more, it will just reflect

00:52:39.659 --> 00:52:40.909
it and go right back.
 

00:52:40.909 --> 00:52:42.079
And when will those lines meet?
 

00:52:42.079 --> 00:52:46.809
They'll meet at infinity.
 

00:52:46.809 --> 00:52:48.699
So I want to do one thing.
 

00:52:48.699 --> 00:52:50.389
I want to show you something.
 

00:52:50.389 --> 00:52:53.510
Here is a spherical mirror I've
cut out.

00:52:53.510 --> 00:52:57.130
I want to send a parallel beam.
 

00:52:57.130 --> 00:53:01.548
I've already shown you that
this should go through the focal

00:53:01.548 --> 00:53:04.920
point, because it's the path of
least time.

00:53:04.920 --> 00:53:07.911
But you can say,
"How do I know once again

00:53:07.911 --> 00:53:10.579
this is the same as i =
r?"

00:53:10.579 --> 00:53:13.690
Suppose you grew up on
incidence = reflection.

00:53:13.690 --> 00:53:16.000
I'm not going to reassure you
continuously.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:19.610
I'm going to do it one last
time, okay?

00:53:19.610 --> 00:53:20.849
Don't ever ask me again.
 

00:53:20.849 --> 00:53:22.139
It's the last time.
 

00:53:22.139 --> 00:53:24.869
I'm going to show you that
Principle of Least Time is the

00:53:24.869 --> 00:53:25.989
same as i = r.
 

00:53:25.989 --> 00:53:27.530
I don't want to do it over.
 

00:53:27.530 --> 00:53:30.179
Here's the last time we're
going to do this.

00:53:30.179 --> 00:53:31.659
So what's our question?
 

00:53:31.659 --> 00:53:35.271
Question is,
if I draw a tangent to that

00:53:35.271 --> 00:53:39.440
graph and drew the normal to
that tangent,

00:53:39.440 --> 00:53:44.452
right, we want to know that
that angle a will be

00:53:44.452 --> 00:53:47.329
equal to that angle b.
 

00:53:47.329 --> 00:53:49.489
That's what we want to show.
 

00:53:49.489 --> 00:53:51.630
But where will this go?
 

00:53:51.630 --> 00:53:54.728
If that's a circle,
if it's a spherical mirror,

00:53:54.728 --> 00:53:58.434
you draw a normal to the
tangent, it will go through the

00:53:58.434 --> 00:54:00.119
center of the sphere.
 

00:54:00.119 --> 00:54:01.059
You understand?
 

00:54:01.059 --> 00:54:07.159
And this one is supposed to go
to the focal point.

00:54:07.159 --> 00:54:12.630
Now let this height be h.
 

00:54:12.630 --> 00:54:14.920
Now let this angle is also
a.

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:20.782
This figure is too small,
so let me draw you a bigger

00:54:20.782 --> 00:54:23.489
figure so you can see.
 

00:54:23.489 --> 00:54:29.148
This is sort of exaggerated so
you've got to be a little

00:54:29.148 --> 00:54:35.012
careful that the--let's call
that a and that's also

00:54:35.012 --> 00:54:36.349
a.
 

00:54:36.349 --> 00:54:38.670
Let's call this b.
 

00:54:38.670 --> 00:54:41.150
This is f and this is
R.

00:54:41.150 --> 00:54:42.260
I hope you understand why.
 

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:44.630
That's the important part.
 

00:54:44.630 --> 00:54:48.059
This mirror is locally
tangential to that line,

00:54:48.059 --> 00:54:49.849
tangent to the circle.
 

00:54:49.849 --> 00:54:53.360
And the normal to the circle is
pointing towards the center.

00:54:53.360 --> 00:54:55.139
That's the way circles work.
 

00:54:55.139 --> 00:54:57.213
You draw a perpendicular from
the circumference,

00:54:57.213 --> 00:54:59.244
you hit the center,
but that's looking like the

00:54:59.244 --> 00:55:01.320
plane mirror for that particular
light ray.

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:03.949
That light ray doesn't care if
you bend it somewhere else.

00:55:03.949 --> 00:55:06.686
As far as this ray is
concerned, you are a plane

00:55:06.686 --> 00:55:07.210
mirror.
 

00:55:07.210 --> 00:55:09.030
You want that angle to be equal
to that angle.

00:55:09.030 --> 00:55:12.030
That's what I want to show you.
 

00:55:12.030 --> 00:55:18.347
So let's take this height h
here, and you can notice that

00:55:18.347 --> 00:55:24.889
tan b = h/f and
tan a = h/R.

00:55:24.889 --> 00:55:26.030
Can you see that?
 

00:55:26.030 --> 00:55:29.449
That's b and a?
 

00:55:29.449 --> 00:55:34.639
For small angles,
for a small angle,

00:55:34.639 --> 00:55:38.364
I remind you again and again,
sinθ is roughly

00:55:38.364 --> 00:55:41.371
θ and
tanθ is roughly

00:55:41.371 --> 00:55:44.507
θ and
cosθ is roughly 1

00:55:44.507 --> 00:55:47.579
corrections of order
θ^(2).

00:55:47.579 --> 00:55:50.280
So we delete the tan.
 

00:55:50.280 --> 00:55:54.067
And if you use the fact that
R = 2f,

00:55:54.067 --> 00:55:58.010
it becomes h over
2f, you can see that

00:55:58.010 --> 00:56:00.019
a = b/2.
 

00:56:00.019 --> 00:56:05.730
So a = b/2.
 

00:56:05.730 --> 00:56:09.469
That means b is twice as
big as a,

00:56:09.469 --> 00:56:12.842
but in any triangle,
the external angle is sum of

00:56:12.842 --> 00:56:16.826
the internal opposite angles,
therefore if this is 2a

00:56:16.826 --> 00:56:21.949
and this guy is a,
that's also a.

00:56:21.949 --> 00:56:26.088
That means the angle of
incidence is the angle of

00:56:26.088 --> 00:56:27.210
reflection.
 

00:56:27.210 --> 00:56:31.601
So what I'm telling you is,
you can always go back to angle

00:56:31.601 --> 00:56:34.480
of incidence = angle of
reflection,

00:56:34.480 --> 00:56:37.518
but it's going to take more
work because you have to find

00:56:37.518 --> 00:56:38.280
the tangent.
 

00:56:38.280 --> 00:56:40.289
You've got to draw the normal
to the tangent.

00:56:40.289 --> 00:56:42.920
You've got to find the angle
with respect to that normal and

00:56:42.920 --> 00:56:44.170
equate it with that angle.
 

00:56:44.170 --> 00:56:47.989
You will find in fact every ray
goes through f.

00:56:47.989 --> 00:56:53.039
But it works only in the small
angle approximation.

00:56:53.039 --> 00:56:58.612
The small angle basically means
your object is not too tall

00:56:58.612 --> 00:57:02.360
compared to the radius of the
mirror.

00:57:02.360 --> 00:57:05.650
That's because if the object is
comparable, then the

00:57:05.650 --> 00:57:09.005
approximation I made that a
circle will approximate a

00:57:09.005 --> 00:57:11.070
parabola is no longer valid.
 

00:57:11.070 --> 00:57:13.170
So remember,
if you took a real parabola,

00:57:13.170 --> 00:57:15.690
if you have the stomach,
you can do the following

00:57:15.690 --> 00:57:16.530
calculation.
 

00:57:16.530 --> 00:57:19.440
Take a real parabola,
you will find angle of

00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:22.349
incidence is angle of reflection
exactly.

00:57:22.349 --> 00:57:24.230
Whenever you draw a line,
horizontal line,

00:57:24.230 --> 00:57:26.340
that hits the mirror,
comes to the focal point,

00:57:26.340 --> 00:57:28.599
if you find the local value of
the perpendicular,

00:57:28.599 --> 00:57:31.860
you'll find i = r,
no matter how far you go.

00:57:31.860 --> 00:57:33.900
But if you approximate it by a
spherical mirror,

00:57:33.900 --> 00:57:36.025
we have seen,
the spherical mirror is only an

00:57:36.025 --> 00:57:39.981
approximation to the parabola,
when you can drop the

00:57:39.981 --> 00:57:42.119
x^(2) term.
 

00:57:42.119 --> 00:57:47.577
Okay, so we have seen the
Principle of Least Time is able

00:57:47.577 --> 00:57:52.742
to give us i = r,
Snell's law and focusing of a

00:57:52.742 --> 00:57:54.010
parabola.
 

00:57:54.010 --> 00:57:57.525
Now I want to consider the
following thing:

00:57:57.525 --> 00:58:02.465
just because a parabola can
focus light ray at infinity to a

00:58:02.465 --> 00:58:07.739
focal point does not mean if you
put a finite object at a finite

00:58:07.739 --> 00:58:13.550
distance from it,
it will form a clear image.

00:58:13.550 --> 00:58:16.039
It's only an approximation.
 

00:58:16.039 --> 00:58:19.338
And I will show you what we
normally get from geometrical

00:58:19.338 --> 00:58:19.869
optics.
 

00:58:19.869 --> 00:58:22.380
I'll remind you what we know
from geometrical optics.

00:58:22.380 --> 00:58:24.516
Geometrical optics tells you
the following:

00:58:24.516 --> 00:58:27.414
if you have an object of height
h at a distance u from the

00:58:27.414 --> 00:58:30.670
mirror and you want to know
where the image will be formed,

00:58:30.670 --> 00:58:34.559
you first draw a horizontal
line whose fate you know.

00:58:34.559 --> 00:58:39.389
It has to go through the focal
point.

00:58:39.389 --> 00:58:43.289
The second one says you draw a
line through the focal point and

00:58:43.289 --> 00:58:45.429
it's got to come out horizontal.
 

00:58:45.429 --> 00:58:47.139
How do I know that?
 

00:58:47.139 --> 00:58:49.900
I know that if I run the ray
backwards,

00:58:49.900 --> 00:58:53.050
a horizontal ray will go
through the focal point,

00:58:53.050 --> 00:58:55.889
but if going backwards,
it's a good idea,

00:58:55.889 --> 00:58:59.947
namely least time,
it's also a good idea going

00:58:59.947 --> 00:59:00.849
forward.
 

00:59:00.849 --> 00:59:04.869
That's why we know that
parallel will go through focus.

00:59:04.869 --> 00:59:06.610
Through focus it will come out
parallel.

00:59:06.610 --> 00:59:10.969
So you join them and you've got
the image there.

00:59:10.969 --> 00:59:20.170
And that's at a distance
v at a height

00:59:20.170 --> 00:59:24.980
h_2.
 

00:59:24.980 --> 00:59:28.969
So I'm now going to use ideas
of geometrical optics,

00:59:28.969 --> 00:59:32.112
having shown you enough times
that least time and geometrical

00:59:32.112 --> 00:59:34.409
optics are equal,
to find the usual relation

00:59:34.409 --> 00:59:38.300
between u,
v and f.

00:59:38.300 --> 00:59:40.099
So how do we do that?
 

00:59:40.099 --> 00:59:45.963
We say, take that triangle with
angle alpha and that with angle

00:59:45.963 --> 00:59:50.030
alpha and draw a triangle like
this here.

00:59:50.030 --> 00:59:54.139
Then you equate tangent of this
angle to tangent of that angle.

00:59:54.139 --> 01:00:04.097
Then you find tanα
= h_1 divided

01:00:04.097 --> 01:00:08.994
by u - f,
that distance,

01:00:08.994 --> 01:00:13.730
= h_2/f.
 

01:00:13.730 --> 01:00:15.260
Actually, there's a tiny bit.
 

01:00:15.260 --> 01:00:16.289
It's not quite f.
 

01:00:16.289 --> 01:00:19.059
It's (f −
x)^(2), but x^(2) is

01:00:19.059 --> 01:00:22.679
negligible compared to f,
so we won't worry about that.

01:00:22.679 --> 01:00:26.340
You see this triangle here?
 

01:00:26.340 --> 01:00:27.860
That height is certainly
h_2.

01:00:27.860 --> 01:00:29.460
That length is not quite
f.

01:00:29.460 --> 01:00:32.324
f goes all the way to
the mirror, but if I drop a

01:00:32.324 --> 01:00:34.876
perpendicular here,
there's a tiny little x

01:00:34.876 --> 01:00:35.449
inside.
 

01:00:35.449 --> 01:00:36.590
I'm now showing you that
x.

01:00:36.590 --> 01:00:38.719
I've been neglecting it.
 

01:00:38.719 --> 01:00:41.130
In other words,
you really should put an f -

01:00:41.130 --> 01:00:43.907
x, but x is quadratic
in the small numbers,

01:00:43.907 --> 01:00:45.690
so we're not going to keep it.
 

01:00:45.690 --> 01:00:48.300
Then draw another similar
triangle.

01:00:48.300 --> 01:00:52.730
This angle β
is the same as this angle

01:00:52.730 --> 01:00:53.679
β.
 

01:00:53.679 --> 01:00:58.610
So let's say tan β
found two ways it's equal.

01:00:58.610 --> 01:01:01.730
This one, tan β
on the top,

01:01:01.730 --> 01:01:05.530
you can see is the
h_1/f

01:01:05.530 --> 01:01:10.139
and that's going to = the tan
β of this triangle,

01:01:10.139 --> 01:01:15.284
which will be
h_2 divided by

01:01:15.284 --> 01:01:17.039
v - f.
 

01:01:17.039 --> 01:01:18.610
These are the two conditions
you get.

01:01:18.610 --> 01:01:37.219
 
 

01:01:37.219 --> 01:01:39.920
Okay, I may want to draw bigger
pictures.

01:01:39.920 --> 01:01:42.409
Can you guys see this,
or there's no hope?

01:01:42.409 --> 01:01:44.429
Can you see in the last row?
 

01:01:44.429 --> 01:01:45.349
Cannot.
 

01:01:45.349 --> 01:01:48.695
You should tell me when you
cannot, because I'll be happy to

01:01:48.695 --> 01:01:49.320
fix that.
 

01:01:49.320 --> 01:01:51.340
So let me draw this bigger.
 

01:01:51.340 --> 01:01:54.010
The reason that I'm drawing
everything small is that I don't

01:01:54.010 --> 01:01:56.728
want the rays to go too far up
the axis, but I'm not going to

01:01:56.728 --> 01:01:57.679
worry about that.
 

01:01:57.679 --> 01:01:59.380
So let's make sure you can see
the rays.

01:01:59.380 --> 01:02:06.074
There's one guy who did that,
one which did that,

01:02:06.074 --> 01:02:07.469
correct?
 

01:02:07.469 --> 01:02:11.971
This is α
and that is α

01:02:11.971 --> 01:02:17.400
and this is β
and this is β`.

01:02:17.400 --> 01:02:19.679
That's all I've done now.
 

01:02:19.679 --> 01:02:23.976
So tan α
= h_1 divided

01:02:23.976 --> 01:02:26.902
by this side,
where u is the distance

01:02:26.902 --> 01:02:29.077
from the mirror,
you take away f,

01:02:29.077 --> 01:02:32.797
because that's f. That's
h_1 over u -

01:02:32.797 --> 01:02:33.329
f.
 

01:02:33.329 --> 01:02:36.690
It's the same as tan alpha
measured on this triangle.

01:02:36.690 --> 01:02:38.641
That tan α
is

01:02:38.641 --> 01:02:43.630
h_2/f -
a tiny portion,

01:02:43.630 --> 01:02:48.619
which is the x,
which I'm dropping.

01:02:48.619 --> 01:02:51.239
But similarly for β,
you have a similar rule.

01:02:51.239 --> 01:02:55.659
So here's all you can get out
of these two rays.

01:02:55.659 --> 01:03:04.505
So let's multiply this one and
this one and that one and that

01:03:04.505 --> 01:03:05.389
one.
 

01:03:05.389 --> 01:03:08.791
So I'll get
h_1h_2

01:03:08.791 --> 01:03:12.449
over u - f times v
- f.

01:03:12.449 --> 01:03:14.889
I'm going to cross multiply
like that.

01:03:14.889 --> 01:03:18.217
It =
h_1h_2

01:03:18.217 --> 01:03:20.639
over f^(2).
 

01:03:20.639 --> 01:03:26.353
That tells you,
u - f times v - f

01:03:26.353 --> 01:03:29.210
= f^(2).
 

01:03:29.210 --> 01:03:32.438
You may not have seen it this
way, but it's a very symmetric

01:03:32.438 --> 01:03:33.969
way to write the equation.
 

01:03:33.969 --> 01:03:37.353
If you measure all distances,
not from this point here but

01:03:37.353 --> 01:03:41.034
from the focal point,
then it says u - f times

01:03:41.034 --> 01:03:43.510
v - f equals
f^(2).

01:03:43.510 --> 01:03:45.670
But let's make contact with
what we all know.

01:03:45.670 --> 01:03:51.885
So let's open out the brackets,
so I get uv - uf - vf f

01:03:51.885 --> 01:03:55.050
squared = f^(2).
 

01:03:55.050 --> 01:03:57.670
You cancel that guy.
 

01:03:57.670 --> 01:04:04.679
Then you get uf vf =
uv.

01:04:04.679 --> 01:04:10.699
Now divide everything by
uvf.

01:04:10.699 --> 01:04:20.565
You divided everything by
uvf, you'll get 1/v

01:04:20.565 --> 01:04:23.489
1/u = 1/f.
 

01:04:23.489 --> 01:04:27.030
Anyway, this is derived by
standard geometrical optics,

01:04:27.030 --> 01:04:30.440
without going back to the
Principle of Least Time.

01:04:30.440 --> 01:04:31.329
So this is the result.
 

01:04:31.329 --> 01:04:33.596
But there's one more result,
because you've got two

01:04:33.596 --> 01:04:35.500
equations, you can learn one
more thing.

01:04:35.500 --> 01:04:38.599
You can ask yourself,
what's the ratio of the object

01:04:38.599 --> 01:04:40.119
size to the image size?
 

01:04:40.119 --> 01:04:43.659
You can say,
what is h_2/h

01:04:43.659 --> 01:04:45.429
_1?
 

01:04:45.429 --> 01:04:49.282
So
h_2/h_1

01:04:49.282 --> 01:04:54.219
is f divided by u
-f.

01:04:54.219 --> 01:04:55.760
Or let me write it another way,
it's easier.

01:04:55.760 --> 01:05:01.746
h_1/h_2
= (u −

01:05:01.746 --> 01:05:03.090
f)/f.
 

01:05:03.090 --> 01:05:07.710
That's equal to u/f - 1.
 

01:05:07.710 --> 01:05:13.010
u/f is u times
1/f and 1/f is

01:05:13.010 --> 01:05:16.230
1/u  1 over v - 1.
 

01:05:16.230 --> 01:05:21.295
And if you do that,
you'll find it's just u

01:05:21.295 --> 01:05:22.949
over v.
 

01:05:22.949 --> 01:05:26.465
So the ratio of the object size
to the image size is just the

01:05:26.465 --> 01:05:29.570
ratio of the object distance to
the image distance.

01:05:29.570 --> 01:05:33.722
And people sometimes define a
magnification M to be

01:05:33.722 --> 01:05:35.179
−u/v.
 

01:05:35.179 --> 01:05:38.626
What they mean by the - sign is
that if this comes out negative,

01:05:38.626 --> 01:05:40.980
the object is in the upside
down version.

01:05:40.980 --> 01:05:45.170
The image is an upside down
version of the object.

01:05:45.170 --> 01:05:47.487
In this problem u and
v are both positive,

01:05:47.487 --> 01:05:49.130
then M will come out
negative.

01:05:49.130 --> 01:05:54.219
It just means it is that much
bigger, but flipped upside down.

01:05:54.219 --> 01:05:56.764
In some other mirrors,
you will find v is

01:05:56.764 --> 01:05:58.929
negative because the image is
virtual.

01:05:58.929 --> 01:06:00.929
Then it will mean M is
positive.

01:06:00.929 --> 01:06:02.630
That means the object is
upright.

01:06:02.630 --> 01:06:06.842
That's when you look into the
mirror, the bathroom mirror,

01:06:06.842 --> 01:06:10.760
then your image has the same
orientation as your face,

01:06:10.760 --> 01:06:12.239
not upside down.
 

01:06:12.239 --> 01:06:16.980
Then M will be positive.
 

01:06:16.980 --> 01:06:20.809
Okay, now here's a question one
can ask.

01:06:20.809 --> 01:06:25.164
When you do geometric optics,
there's a question one can ask,

01:06:25.164 --> 01:06:28.719
which usually occurs about 30
years afterwards.

01:06:28.719 --> 01:06:30.050
I never asked that question.
 

01:06:30.050 --> 01:06:32.289
I kept doing all the problems.
 

01:06:32.289 --> 01:06:35.753
Then a few years ago,
when I started teaching this

01:06:35.753 --> 01:06:39.922
course, I began to ask myself,
you know, you can always draw

01:06:39.922 --> 01:06:42.679
two rays and they will always
meet.

01:06:42.679 --> 01:06:45.199
What if I draw another one?
 

01:06:45.199 --> 01:06:51.030
What if I draw one that goes
like this?

01:06:51.030 --> 01:06:52.000
How do I know it will come here?
 

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:55.090
A lot of pictures show you that
coming here, but should it come

01:06:55.090 --> 01:06:55.440
here?
 

01:06:55.440 --> 01:06:59.320
Maybe it won't,
so let me check this thing.

01:06:59.320 --> 01:07:03.077
Let me make sure that if I have
a ray coming to the center of

01:07:03.077 --> 01:07:06.710
this, it will also end up where
the other two guys came.

01:07:06.710 --> 01:07:09.960
Well, if you do the center,
remember, it's angle of

01:07:09.960 --> 01:07:13.925
incidence = angle of reflection,
that means the tangent of the

01:07:13.925 --> 01:07:15.289
angles are equal.
 

